`Option<T>` is Rust's way of expressing a value that may or may not exist — replacing null pointers.

```rust
fn find_first_even(nums: &[i32]) -> Option<i32> {
    for &n in nums {
        if n % 2 == 0 {
            return Some(n);
        }
    }
    None
}

fn main() {
    let nums = [1, 3, 4, 7];
    match find_first_even(&nums) {
        Some(v) => println!("Found: {}", v),
        None    => println!("Not found"),
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**
- `Option<i32>` is either `Some(value)` or `None`.
- `match` exhaustively handles both variants — the compiler enforces that you handle `None`.
- This is much safer than returning `-1` or a null pointer to signal "no result".

