Recursive types in Rust require `Box` to give the compiler a known size.

```rust
enum List<T> {
    Nil,
    Cons(T, Box<List<T>>),
}

impl<T: Clone> List<T> {
    fn new() -> Self {
        List::Nil
    }

    fn push_front(self, value: T) -> Self {
        List::Cons(value, Box::new(self))
    }

    fn len(&self) -> usize {
        match self {
            List::Nil         => 0,
            List::Cons(_, rest) => 1 + rest.len(),
        }
    }

    fn to_vec(&self) -> Vec<T> {
        match self {
            List::Nil              => vec![],
            List::Cons(val, rest)  => {
                let mut v = vec![val.clone()];
                v.extend(rest.to_vec());
                v
            }
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let list = List::new()
        .push_front(3)
        .push_front(2)
        .push_front(1);

    println!("Length: {}", list.len());
    let parts: Vec<String> = list.to_vec().iter().map(|x| x.to_string()).collect();
    println!("{}", parts.join(" "));
}
```

**Explanation:**
- `enum List<T>` is either `Nil` (empty) or `Cons(value, tail)` where `tail` is boxed.
- `Box<List<T>>` allocates the tail on the heap, giving the recursive type a finite known size on the stack.
- `push_front` consumes `self` and wraps it in a new `Cons` node — no mutation needed.
- `len` and `to_vec` recurse by pattern matching — the `Nil` arm is the base case.
- `T: Clone` bound is needed for `to_vec` to clone values out of the list.

